{
  "What is a reference frame?": "",
  "A fixed point in space": "",
  "A type of laboratory equipment": "",
  "A unit of measurement": "",
  "A coordinate system used to measure position and motion": "",
  "A reference frame is a coordinate system with respect to which position, velocity, and other quantities are measured. All motion is relative to a chosen reference frame.": "",
  "How do you find the velocity of A relative to B?": "",
  "v_AB = v_A - v_B": "",
  "v_AB = v_A + v_B": "",
  "v_AB = v_A / v_B": "",
  "v_AB = v_A * v_B": "",
  "The velocity of A relative to B is v_AB = v_A - v_B. This formula gives the velocity of object A as observed from object B's reference frame.": "",
  "Two cars moving at 60 and 40 km/h in the same direction: relative velocity?": "",
  "2400 km/h": "",
  "100 km/h": "",
  "50 km/h": "",
  "20 km/h": "",
  "For objects moving in the same direction, relative velocity = 60 - 40 = 20 km/h. The faster car appears to move at 20 km/h as seen from the slower car.": "",
  "What is an inertial frame?": "",
  "A non-accelerating frame where Newton's laws apply directly": "",
  "Any frame attached to Earth": "",
  "A rotating frame": "",
  "A frame moving faster than light": "",
  "An inertial frame is a reference frame that is not accelerating (moving at constant velocity or at rest). Newton's laws of motion hold directly in inertial frames without needing corrections.": "",
  "When does Galilean relativity break down?": "",
  "Only in non-inertial reference frames": "",
  "It never breaks down under any conditions": "",
  "At speeds close to the speed of light": "",
  "At very low speeds near absolute zero": "",
  "Galilean relativity (simple velocity addition) breaks down at speeds approaching the speed of light (3 x 10^8 m/s). At those speeds, Einstein's special relativity must be used instead.": "",
  "Why does rain appear angled when you run?": "",
  "Your motion changes the rain's velocity relative to you": "",
  "The wind always blows horizontally": "",
  "Rain never falls straight": "",
  "It's an optical illusion": "",
  "When you run, your horizontal velocity adds to the rain's vertical velocity in your reference frame, creating a diagonal (angled) relative velocity. The rain appears to come at you from an angle.": "",
  "In a river crossing, the boat's ground velocity is found by:": "",
  "Using only the boat's speed": "",
  "Dividing boat speed by current speed": "",
  "Vector sum of boat velocity relative to water and water velocity relative to ground": "",
  "Subtracting all velocities": "",
  "The boat's velocity relative to the ground equals the vector sum of its velocity relative to the water plus the water's velocity relative to the ground: v_BG = v_BW + v_WG.": "",
  "Two cars approach each other, one at 50 km/h and the other at 60 km/h. What is their relative speed?": "",
  "10 km/h": "",
  "55 km/h": "",
  "110 km/h": "",
  "3000 km/h": "",
  "When two objects move toward each other (opposite directions), their relative speed is the sum: 50 + 60 = 110 km/h. Each car sees the other approaching at 110 km/h.": "",
  "Is it possible for an object to be at rest in one frame but moving in another?": "",
  "No, an object is either moving or at rest regardless of frame": "",
  "Yes, motion depends on the reference frame of the observer": "",
  "Only if the object is in outer space far from any planet": "",
  "Only if the object is accelerating at the same time": "",
  "Motion is relative. A passenger sitting on a moving train is at rest in the train's frame but moving in the ground frame. There is no absolute state of motion or rest.": "",
  "A person walks at 2 m/s on a train moving at 30 m/s in the same direction. What is the person's speed relative to the ground?": "",
  "28 m/s": "",
  "32 m/s": "",
  "30 m/s": "",
  "60 m/s": "",
  "When moving in the same direction, velocities add: 30 + 2 = 32 m/s relative to the ground. The person's ground speed is the sum of the train speed and walking speed.": "",
  "What does 'relative motion' mean?": "",
  "The motion of one object as observed from the perspective of another object": "",
  "The motion of an object that is related to a family member of the observer": "",
  "The motion of an object that occurs only relative to the center of Earth": "",
  "The motion of an object that is approximately but not exactly measured": "",
  "Relative motion describes how one object moves as seen from the perspective of another. All motion is relative because there is no absolute fixed point in the universe.": "",
  "What does 'relative velocity' mean?": "",
  "The velocity of one object as measured in the reference frame of another object": "",
  "The average velocity calculated by dividing total displacement by total time": "",
  "The velocity that remains constant when no forces act on an object": "",
  "The velocity an object must have to escape Earth's gravitational pull": "",
  "Relative velocity is the velocity of object A as observed from the reference frame of object B. It is calculated as v_AB = v_A - v_B.": "",
  "What does 'observer' mean in the context of reference frames?": "",
  "The person or object whose reference frame is being used to measure motion": "",
  "A special instrument used in laboratories to measure very fast objects": "",
  "A person who watches an experiment but does not participate in it at all": "",
  "The fastest-moving object in any given physics problem about motion": "",
  "In physics, an observer is the person or object whose reference frame is used to make measurements. Different observers in different frames may measure different velocities for the same object.": "",
  "What is a 'non-inertial frame'?": "",
  "An accelerating reference frame where Newton's laws need correction terms": "",
  "A reference frame that is perfectly at rest and never moves at all": "",
  "A reference frame used only in outer space far from any planets": "",
  "A reference frame that moves at constant velocity in a straight line": "",
  "A non-inertial frame is accelerating (speeding up, slowing down, or rotating). Newton's laws do not directly apply in non-inertial frames without adding fictitious forces like the centrifugal force.": "",
  "What does 'Galilean velocity addition' refer to?": "",
  "The rule that velocities simply add or subtract between reference frames at everyday speeds": "",
  "The theory that heavier objects fall faster than lighter ones in Earth's gravity": "",
  "The principle that all objects in free fall accelerate at exactly 9.8 m/s^2": "",
  "The law that says no object can exceed the speed of light in a vacuum": "",
  "Galilean velocity addition says that velocities in different reference frames simply add or subtract: v_AG = v_AB + v_BG. This works well at everyday speeds but breaks down near the speed of light.": "",
  "What does it mean to say 'all motion is relative'?": "",
  "Motion can only be described with respect to a chosen reference point or frame": "",
  "All objects in the universe are constantly moving and can never be at rest": "",
  "Motion is only an illusion and no objects actually change their position": "",
  "All objects move at the same speed relative to the center of the universe": "",
  "Saying 'all motion is relative' means there is no absolute state of motion or rest. Whether an object is moving or stationary depends entirely on what reference frame you choose.": "",
  "What does 'ground frame' or 'Earth frame' mean?": "",
  "A reference frame that treats the surface of the Earth as stationary": "",
  "A reference frame located at the exact center of Earth's core": "",
  "A frame used only for objects that are in contact with the ground": "",
  "A frame that can only measure horizontal motion along the ground": "",
  "The ground frame (Earth frame) treats the surface of the Earth as stationary. Most everyday measurements of position and velocity are made in this frame.": "",
  "What does 'fictitious force' mean in a non-inertial frame?": "",
  "An apparent force that arises from the acceleration of the reference frame itself": "",
  "A force that is completely imaginary and has no measurable physical effect": "",
  "A real force that only exists in outer space far from any gravitational bodies": "",
  "A force that scientists invented to make their equations look more balanced": "",
  "Fictitious (pseudo) forces appear in non-inertial (accelerating) frames to account for the frame's acceleration. Examples include centrifugal force and the Coriolis force. They have real, measurable effects within that frame.": "",
  "What does 'velocity addition' mean?": "",
  "Combining velocities from different reference frames to find velocity in a third frame": "",
  "Adding together the speeds of two objects that collide and stick together": "",
  "Increasing an object's velocity by applying a constant force over a period of time": "",
  "Calculating the total distance by multiplying speed by time for each segment": "",
  "Velocity addition is the process of combining velocities measured in different frames. For example, v_AC = v_AB + v_BC connects velocity of A relative to B with velocity of B relative to C.": "",
  "What is the 'speed of light' and why is it important for relative motion?": "",
  "About 3 x 10^8 m/s; it is the speed limit where Galilean addition breaks down": "",
  "About 340 m/s; it is the speed at which relative motion can no longer be measured": "",
  "About 9.8 m/s; it determines how fast objects fall in free fall near Earth": "",
  "About 1000 m/s; it is the maximum speed at which sound travels through air": "",
  "The speed of light is approximately 3 x 10^8 m/s. At speeds approaching this value, Galilean velocity addition no longer works and must be replaced by Einstein's relativistic formulas.": "",
  "A passenger on a train moving at 25 m/s throws a ball forward at 5 m/s relative to the train. What is the ball's speed relative to the ground?": "",
  "20 m/s": "",
  "25 m/s": "",
  "5 m/s": "",
  "The ball's ground velocity = train velocity + ball's velocity relative to train = 25 + 5 = 30 m/s forward. Both velocities are in the same direction, so they add.": "",
  "A boat heads north at 4 m/s in still water. The river current flows east at 3 m/s. What is the boat's actual speed relative to the ground?": "",
  "7 m/s": "",
  "1 m/s": "",
  "12 m/s": "",
  "North and east are perpendicular, so use the Pythagorean theorem: speed = sqrt(4^2 + 3^2) = sqrt(16 + 9) = sqrt(25) = 5 m/s.": "",
  "A student on a moving bus throws a ball straight up. From the student's perspective, the ball goes up and comes back down. What does a person standing on the sidewalk see?": "",
  "The ball goes straight up and straight down, the same as the student sees": "",
  "The ball follows a parabolic arc because it has both vertical and horizontal velocity": "",
  "The ball flies backward behind the bus because the bus moves out from under it": "",
  "The ball stays perfectly still in midair while the bus moves forward beneath it": "",
  "From the ground, the ball has both vertical velocity (from the throw) and horizontal velocity (from the bus), so it follows a parabolic path. Different frames see different trajectories.": "",
  "A plane flies north at 200 km/h relative to the air. A wind blows from west to east at 50 km/h. What is the plane's speed relative to the ground?": "",
  "150 km/h": "",
  "250 km/h": "",
  "About 206 km/h": "",
  "About 194 km/h": "",
  "The northward and eastward velocities are perpendicular: speed = sqrt(200^2 + 50^2) = sqrt(40000 + 2500) = sqrt(42500) = approximately 206 km/h.": "",
  "A student walks backward at 1 m/s on a moving walkway that travels forward at 2 m/s. What is the student's velocity relative to the ground?": "",
  "3 m/s forward": "",
  "1 m/s forward": "",
  "1 m/s backward": "",
  "2 m/s forward": "",
  "Walking backward at 1 m/s on a walkway moving forward at 2 m/s: ground velocity = 2 + (-1) = 1 m/s forward. The walkway moves faster forward than the student walks backward.": "",
  "Two trains run on parallel tracks. Train A moves east at 80 km/h and Train B moves east at 60 km/h. A passenger on Train B looks at Train A. How fast does Train A appear to move?": "",
  "140 km/h east": "",
  "20 km/h east": "",
  "80 km/h east": "",
  "20 km/h west": "",
  "Relative velocity of A as seen from B = v_A - v_B = 80 - 60 = 20 km/h east. Train A appears to slowly move ahead of Train B at 20 km/h.": "",
  "A student sits in a car at a stoplight. The car next to them starts to roll backward. The student briefly feels like their own car is moving forward. What explains this?": "",
  "The student's car actually did move forward slightly due to engine vibration": "",
  "Relative motion makes the student perceive their car moving when the other car moves": "",
  "Gravity pulled the student's car forward when the other car moved backward": "",
  "The road surface tilted slightly causing both cars to shift position": "",
  "This is a classic example of relative motion perception. When the neighboring car rolls backward, the relative motion between the two cars is the same as if the student's car moved forward.": "",
  "A swimmer swims at 1.5 m/s in still water and needs to cross a river with a 2 m/s current. Can the swimmer reach a point directly across the river?": "",
  "Yes, by swimming straight across and ignoring the current entirely": "",
  "No, because the current speed exceeds the swimmer's speed in still water": "",
  "Yes, by swimming at exactly the same speed as the river current": "",
  "No, because you cannot swim across any river with a current at all": "",
  "To reach a point directly across, the swimmer would need to aim upstream enough to cancel the current. Since the current (2 m/s) exceeds the swimmer's speed (1.5 m/s), they cannot fully compensate and will be carried downstream.": "",
  "A student on a skateboard moving at 3 m/s throws a ball backward at 3 m/s relative to themselves. What is the ball's velocity relative to the ground?": "",
  "6 m/s forward": "",
  "3 m/s backward": "",
  "0 m/s (the ball drops straight down)": "",
  "Ground velocity = skateboard velocity + ball's velocity relative to skateboard = 3 + (-3) = 0 m/s. The ball momentarily has zero horizontal velocity and drops straight down from the ground observer's perspective.": "",
  "A helicopter hovers above a moving truck. A package is dropped from the helicopter. Where does the package land relative to the truck?": "",
  "Directly on the truck because the package has no horizontal velocity": "",
  "Behind the truck because the truck moves forward while the package falls": "",
  "In front of the truck because air resistance pushes the package ahead": "",
  "It lands exactly where it was dropped because gravity acts only downward": "",
  "The hovering helicopter has zero horizontal velocity, so the dropped package also has zero horizontal velocity. The truck moves forward while the package falls straight down, so the package lands behind the truck.": ""
